    "narrative": "The Austin Waves\u2019 starting lineup for May 4th is anchored by **Josh Lowe** (71.44), who represents our strongest play of the day. His matchup against Davis Martin (4.38 xERA) provides a favorable environment for production, bolstered by a 14% platoon edge and wind blowing out at the venue. **Gunnar Henderson** (68.74) and **Heliot Ramos** (65.97) follow closely in effectiveness; **Gunnar Henderson** leverages a significant 14% platoon advantage against Cam Schlittler, while **Heliot Ramos** benefits from a high-upside matchup against Randy V\u00e1squez, whose 4.91 xERA suggests a prime opportunity for **Heliot Ramos** to capitalize on his leadoff positioning. **Vladimir Guerrero Jr.** (65.92) remains a high-floor start despite a slight park penalty, as his high xwOBA and the matchup against Nick Martinez\u2019s 4.59 xERA keep him in the top tier of our output expectations.\n\nWhile the core is set, the bench decision surrounding **Coby Mayo** (41.42) was the most difficult, as he narrowly missed the cut behind lower-tier starts from **Drake Baldwin** and **Liam Hicks**. While **Coby Mayo** offers intrigue, the optimizer prioritized the positional flexibility and platoon advantages of our active catchers against their respective arms. It is important to note that all lineup projections remain contingent on the pending official batting orders; with several players like **Drake Baldwin** and **Nolan Schanuel** projected into high-leverage slots, any shift in the real-time order could necessitate a quick reassessment of our efficiency scores. We remain cautious regarding **Kyle Tucker** (59.10), who faces a sub-4.00 xERA arm in Steven Okert; despite the risk, the need to maintain category depth keeps him active. We continue to monitor the status of **Luis Robert Jr.** and **Luis Garc\u00eda Jr.**, both of whom remain sidelined, complicating our ability to rotate fresh legs into the outfield and middle infield spots.",
